The article is about the mourning and tribute to Walter Mondale, a dedicated patriot and public servant who served as Minnesota's Attorney General, United States Senator, Vice President, and Ambassador to Japan. Mondale's notable achievements include establishing the right to legal counsel for indigent criminal defendants, advocating for fair housing and women's rights, and playing a significant role in international peace treaties and nuclear arms negotiations. He also made history by selecting a woman as his running mate during his 1984 presidential campaign. The article mentions his wife Joan, who was an advocate for the arts, and his children. President Joseph R. Biden Jr. orders that flags be flown at half-staff in honor of Mondale's service and life.